To test:

```
% display record
[run run-echo : echo "HU"]{0xe7b2c91e5d944f5dbcbe5216efc0162c}
[run run-echo : echo "HU"]{0xb9a6ced6ea724d239e405e1938fadea7}
[run run-echo : echo "A"]{0x87e92d44d8c442f29d0d78e72fa7a8a1}
[run run-echo : echo "A"]{0xab5da56231014e36935e2cef4bca767e}
```

When we have bundles like

```
[]{a}
[]{a}
[]{b}
[]{a}
```

We get the following sort keys: `[132432, 132432, 132431, 132432]`

This is not good, because this makes it impossible to insert an item right after the first row in a table (even with #2190 merged in) -- instead, because all bundle rows referring to "a" have the same sort keys, it will be inserted at the end of the table.

To fix this, we should change the logic for `item_sort_key`:

https://github.com/codalab/codalab-worksheets/blob/5b9390b5ecdead2ef736c4e43dc94037f2aeb161/codalab/objects/worksheet.py#L20-L21

We should also do some sort of migration (either a one-time migration or a dynamic migration upon worksheet load) that would correct these duplicate sort keys for existing worksheets.

_From @percyliang on January 28, 2017 16:8_

Currently, the following program fails:

import java.io.*;
import java.util.*;
import java.net.*;

public class A {
  public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception {
    System.out.println(InetAddress.getLocalHost());
  }
}

with an exception:

Exception in thread "main" java.net.UnknownHostException: b1967f4a15f8: b1967f4a15f8: unknown error
	at java.net.InetAddress.getLocalHost(InetAddress.java:1484)
	at A.main(A.java:7)
Caused by: java.net.UnknownHostException: b1967f4a15f8: unknown error
	at java.net.Inet6AddressImpl.lookupAllHostAddr(Native Method)
	at java.net.InetAddress$2.lookupAllHostAddr(InetAddress.java:907)
	at java.net.InetAddress.getAddressesFromNameService(InetAddress.java:1302)
	at java.net.InetAddress.getLocalHost(InetAddress.java:1479)

This is because /etc/hosts doesn't have the line `127.0.0.1 b1967f4a15f8`.  This is fixed if you specify `--request-network`, but seems like we ought make it work even if you don't request network since there's no actual network usage here.

